rthamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Oundle, Ashton, Northampton, England":"Oundle, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom",", , Northampton, England, United Kingdom":"Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Tyndale","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Sussex and Nottinghamshire): variant of   Tindall  . This surname is also established in Jamaica."],"variants":[{"name":"Tindall","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lincolnshire): habitational name from Tynedale, the valley of the river Tyne, or from a place in Cumbria called Tindale, which is situated on a tributary of the South Tyne. The name derives from a British river name <i>Tina</i> (apparently from a Celtic root meaning ‘to flow’) + Old English <i>dæl</i> or Old Norse <i>dalr</i> ‘valley’."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":23,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":36,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Tyndale III was born in 1292, in Oundle, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert de Tyndale II, was 42 and his mother, Francis Jean Hoover, was 27. He had at least 1 son with Joan de Tynedale. He died in 1332, in Norfolk, England, at the age of 40."},"et":{"1292–1332":"1292–1332","1285–Male":"1285–Surnud","1292–Female":"1292–Surnud","1319–1365":"1319–1365","1250–1293":"1250–1293","1265–1325":"1265–1325","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1332":"1332","1365":"1365","1265":"1265","1285":"1285","1250":"1250","1293":"1293","1292":"1292","1319":"1319","1328":"1328","1317":"1317